Use TemplateHaskellQuotes instead of manually constructing Names

This will make the code far easier to maintain going forward. In addition, some
of the internal names that are referenced in `Generics.Deriving.TH.Internal`
have changed in GHC 9.8, so using `TemplateHaskellQuotes` makes the code robust
against these changes.

Generate INLINE [1] pragmas for TH-derived instances

This backports changes to GHC's treatment of derived `Generic(1)` instances in
https://gitlab.haskell.org/ghc/ghc/-/merge_requests/2965, which affect GHC 9.2
or later. The Template Haskell-based implementation is here is adapted from
`linear-generics` (see linear-generics/linear-generics#21).

Support th-abstraction-0.5.*

Only enable TypeInType on pre-8.6 GHCs

After GHC 8.6, `TypeInType`'s functionality was made a part of the `DataKinds`
and `PolyKinds` extensions. Moreover, GHC 9.6 gives a deprecation warning when
using `TypeInType`, so we now have an extra incentive to only enable
`TypeInType` where absolutely necessary.

Fix the build on old GHCs

Fix #82 by relaxing a check

`buildTypeInstance` had some vestigial code which ensured that `Generic1`
instances would only be given to data types whose last type variable has
kind `Type` or `k`. This check really only makes sense on GHC 8.0 or earlier,
however, as those are the only versions in which `Generic1` has the kind
`(Type -> Type) -> Constraint`. On modern GHCs, `Generic1` has the kind
`(k -> Type) -> Constraint`, so we don't need to check the kind of the last
type variable at all.

Fixes #82.
Fix the build on old GHCs

Remove erroneous examples regarding KindSigOptions

The examples given to justify `KindSigOptions` are flawed, as they won't
kind-check even without explicit kind annotations. Until we can come up with
better examples to illustrate how to use `KindSigOptions` (see #81), let's
just remove these examples.

Don't bother building a TypeSubst for derive- methods

The `TypeSubst` that we plumb down to `repField` ultimately serves to
replace the reified type variables from `reifyDatatype` with the actual
type variables that the user supplies. For `make-` functions, the user-supplied
type variables can be different, so using a `TypeSubst` is critical. For
`derive-` functions, however, the domain and range of the substitution are
exactly the same, as they both use reified type variables. Therefore, there
is really no need to build up a substitution at all.

In fact, #80 uncovered a bug in which this substitution was built up
incorrectly, leading to subtle code generation bugs. The easiest fix by far is
to just pass an empty substitution down to `repField`, which avoids the issue
altogether in the common case of `derive-` functions. I'm not 100% convinced
that there aren't still some lingering issues in the lesser-used `make-` code
paths, but I'm disinclined to investigate those unless someone specifically
complains about it.

Fixes #80.

Refactor code in Generics.Deriving.TH

This performs a raft of refactorings in `Generics.Deriving.TH`. Of note is
that the misleadingly-named `GenericKind` is now named `GenericTvbs`, as that
is really what it is about. I also plumb `GenericTvbs` to more places instead
of just `GenericClass`, which enables some further code simplifications.

There is no change in behavior, but this will make a subsequent commit easier
to implement.
